sections.content:
The spread operator creates a **shallow copy**. This means nested objects are not deeply cloned — they're still references to the same object in memory.

```javascript
const original = { name: "Alice", address: { city: "Portland" } };
const copy = { ...original };

copy.address.city = "Seattle";
console.log(original.address.city); // "Seattle" — ALSO changed! 😱
```

For deep copying, use `structuredClone(original)` (modern browsers) or `JSON.parse(JSON.stringify(original))` (classic approach).

