sections.content:
If you omit the initial value, `reduce()` uses the first element as the initial accumulator and starts iterating from the second element. This works for simple sums but can cause confusing bugs with objects.

**Best practice:** Always provide an explicit initial value as the second argument. Your future self will thank you.

```javascript
// ✅ Clear — initial value is 0
array.reduce((sum, n) => sum + n, 0);

// ⚠️ Risky — no initial value
array.reduce((sum, n) => sum + n);
// Crashes on empty array: TypeError!
```

