// HTML: <div id="content"><p>Original <strong>content</strong></p></div>

const content = document.getElementById("content");

// READING innerHTML gives you the HTML as a string
console.log(content.innerHTML);
// "<p>Original <strong>content</strong></p>"

// SETTING innerHTML — it PARSES the HTML!
content.innerHTML = "<h2>New Title</h2><p>New paragraph here.</p>";
// The div now contains an actual <h2> and <p> element!
// The old <p> with <strong> is completely REPLACED.

// You can build complex HTML structures:
content.innerHTML = `
  <div class="card">
    <h3>Product Name</h3>
    <p class="price">$29.99</p>
    <button>Add to Cart</button>
  </div>
`;
// This creates real DOM elements from the HTML string!

// Combining with existing content:
content.innerHTML += "<p>Added at the end</p>";
// ⚠️ WARNING: += with innerHTML is DESTRUCTIVE!
// It serializes the entire content to string, appends, then re-parses.
// All event listeners on existing elements are LOST!

sections.content:
**NEVER use innerHTML with user input!**

```javascript
// ❌ DANGEROUS — User could inject malicious scripts!
const userInput = '<img src=x onerror=alert("HACKED!")>';
document.getElementById('output').innerHTML = userInput;
// This would execute JavaScript! This is called XSS (Cross-Site Scripting)

// ✅ SAFE — textContent treats everything as plain text
document.getElementById('output').textContent = userInput;
// Shows the literal text, no code executes
```

**Rule of thumb:** If the content comes from a user (form inputs, URL parameters, database), ALWAYS use `textContent`. Only use `innerHTML` with strings you've written yourself in your code.

