sections.content:
Great question! There are two separate async operations:

1. **Sending the request and receiving the headers** — `await fetch(url)` completes when the server starts responding (headers received)
2. **Downloading and parsing the entire body** — `await response.json()` completes when all the data has been downloaded and parsed

For large responses (like a huge file), the headers arrive quickly but the body takes time. Separating these steps lets you check the status code and headers BEFORE downloading the entire body.

javascript
const response = await fetch(url);
if (!response.ok) {
  // Don't even bother downloading the body — we know it failed!
  throw new Error(`HTTP ${response.status}`);
}
const data = await response.json(); // Only download if status is OK

